	<h3 class="title is-4 is-spaced mt-6">How to Use It</h3>
	<div class="content">
		<p>
			You can use these <code>tiny</code> and <code>jumbo</code> size controls on many things, like <strong>buttons</strong>, <strong>tags</strong>, <strong>titles</strong>, <strong>icons</strong>, and <strong>form fields</strong>.
			You can control the sizing of elements on specific screen sizes by using <code>is-{tiny/jumbo}-{suffix}</code> where suffix is any of the above.
		</p>

		<h5 class="title is-5">HTML Example with Buttons</h5>
		<pre><code>&lt;div class="buttons"&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-tiny-mobile"&gt;Tiny on Mobile&lt;/button&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-tiny-tablet"&gt;Tiny on Tablet+&lt;/button&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-tiny-desktop"&gt;Tiny on Desktop+&lt;/button&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-tiny-widescreen"&gt;Tiny on Widescreen+&lt;/button&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-tiny-fullhd"&gt;Tiny on FullHD+&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="buttons"&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-jumbo-mobile"&gt;Jumbo on Mobile&lt;/button&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-jumbo-tablet"&gt;Jumbo on Tablet+&lt;/button&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-jumbo-desktop"&gt;Jumbo on Desktop+&lt;/button&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-jumbo-widescreen"&gt;Jumbo on Widescreen+&lt;/button&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-jumbo-fullhd"&gt;Jumbo on FullHD+&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div class="buttons"&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-tiny-tablet-only"&gt;Tiny on Tablet Only&lt;/button&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-tiny-desktop-only"&lt;Tiny on Desktop Only&lt;/button&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-tiny-widescreen-only"&gt;Tiny on Widescreen Only&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div class="buttons"&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-jumbo-tablet-only"&gt;Jumbo on Tablet Only&lt;/button&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-jumbo-desktop-only"&gt;Jumbo on Desktop Only&lt;/button&gt;
	&lt;button class="button is-jumbo-widescreen-only"&gt;Jumbo on Widescreen Only&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>

		<div class="buttons">
			<button class="button is-tiny-mobile">Tiny on Mobile</button>
			<button class="button is-tiny-tablet">Tiny on Tablet+</button>
			<button class="button is-tiny-desktop">Tiny on Desktop+</button>
			<button class="button is-tiny-widescreen">Tiny on Widescreen+</button>
			<button class="button is-tiny-fullhd">Tiny on FullHD+</button>
		</div>

		<div class="buttons">
			<button class="button is-jumbo-mobile">Jumbo on Mobile</button>
			<button class="button is-jumbo-tablet">Jumbo on Tablet+</button>
			<button class="button is-jumbo-desktop">Jumbo on Desktop+</button>
			<button class="button is-jumbo-widescreen">Jumbo on Widescreen+</button>
			<button class="button is-jumbo-fullhd">Jumbo on FullHD+</button>
		</div>
		<div class="buttons">
			<button class="button is-tiny-tablet-only">Tiny on Tablet Only</button>
			<button class="button is-tiny-desktop-only">Tiny on Desktop Only</button>
			<button class="button is-tiny-widescreen-only">Tiny on Widescreen Only</button>
		</div>

		<div class="buttons">
			<button class="button is-jumbo-tablet-only">Jumbo on Tablet Only</button>
			<button class="button is-jumbo-desktop-only">Jumbo on Desktop Only</button>
			<button class="button is-jumbo-widescreen-only">Jumbo on Widescreen Only</button>
		</div>

		<span class="icon is-tiny-desktop">
			<i class="fas fa-home"></i>
		</span>
	</div>

	<h3 class="title is-4 is-spaced mt-6">Text Sizing</h3>
	<div class="content">
		<p>This extension also lets you control text size in new ways. You can make text:</p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Extra small or large</strong> using <code>is-tiny-{size}-{suffix}</code> or <code>is-jumbo-{size}-{suffix}</code> along with Bulma's default text sizes (like <code>is-1</code> for largest to <code>is-7</code> for smallest).</li>
			<li>
				<strong>Change text size based on screen or for printing:</strong>
				<ul>
					<li><strong>For screens:</strong> Use classes like <code>is-size-1-tiny-desktop</code> (meaning "tiny size 1 on desktop screens").</li>
					<li><strong>For printing:</strong> Use classes like <code>is-size-4-jumbo-print</code> (meaning "jumbo size 4 when printed").</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
		</ul>
		<h5 class="title is-5">HTML Example (Responsive Typography)</h5>
		<pre>
		<code>&lt;p class="is-size-7-tiny-mobile"&gt;This text is tiny on mobile.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="is-size-1-jumbo-desktop"&gt;This text is jumbo on desktop.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="is-size-4-tiny-print"&gt;This text is tiny specifically for print.&lt;/p&gt;</code>
		</pre>
		<p class="is-size-7-tiny-mobile">This text is tiny on mobile.</p>
		<p class="is-size-1-jumbo-desktop">This text is jumbo on desktop.</p>
		<p class="is-size-4-tiny-print">This text is tiny specifically for print.</p>
	</div>
</div>